{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.12,0.15,0.01,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32530"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"443"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49538"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-month history of discomfort around her eyes associated with double vision. She has never had any ophthalmological problems before. Her only other health issues are some recent weight loss and occasional palpitations. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orbital cellulitis","Lymphoma of the orbit","Orbital pseudotumour","Sarcoidosis","Thyroid ophthalmopathy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has classic signs of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid ophthalmopathy\u003C/strong\u003E (thyroid eye disease), although such signs usually occur in younger patients aged 20-50 years. Older patients aged 60-80 tend to have fewer signs except visual loss and are often misdiagnosed. There are signs of thyroid eye disease of the right eye including proptosis, conjunctival injection, upper eyelid retraction with increased scleral show and limitation in adduction of the right eye plus limitation in elevation of her left eye. The limitation of adduction and elevation explains the patient\u0027s double vision and is due to swollen tight right medial rectus and left inferior rectus muscles. Along with the history of palpitations and weight loss, the most likely diagnosis is Graves\u0027 disease with associated thyroid ophthalmopathy. Thyroid eye disease is usually bilateral but can be quite asymmetric. In this patient\u0027s age group with apparent unilateral proptosis, thyroid eye disease is a far more common cause than lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrbital cellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is likely to present with a shorter time frame with more significant evidence of inflammation and erythema of the periorbital soft tissues and globe and possible optic nerve involvement causing decreased visual acuity and colour vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma of the orbit\u003C/strong\u003E may present in an indolent fashion with painless proptosis.  It may cause unexplained weight loss but often presents with a palpable orbital mass and may be associated with pain or swelling.  Despite the elderly age, thyroid eye disease is still more common than lymphoma as a cause of unilateral proptosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrbital pseudotumour\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as idiopathic orbital inflammation) is a diagnosis of exclusion which may present in a similar fashion to thyroid ophthalmopathy. However, the associated systemic thyroid symptoms make thyroid ophthalmopathy more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the orbit and present with proptosis, but it typically involves other organ systems and is less likely to cause the specific eyelid changes seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid eye disease is the most common cause of apparent unilateral proptosis in older patients.","Thyroid eye disease can present with asymmetric or unilateral involvement, especially in older patients."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders.","Bahn RS. Graves\u0027 ophthalmopathy. New England Journal of  Medicine. 2010 Feb 25;362(8):726-38. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20181974/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32530"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15924"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15924"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/046ee9ef-3c28-436b-86a4-2ea1e3539b13.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/046ee9ef-3c28-436b-86a4-2ea1e3539b13.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":379}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32530"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-28T17:22:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-04T16:41:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"520"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionR